<article class="article">
  <div class="article-label">AI / Security — May 2026</div>
  <h1>The Agent Identity Gap</h1>
  <div class="article-meta">matterunknown · May 2026 · 7 min read</div>

  <p>There's a useful thought experiment in security: imagine you receive a letter. The envelope is properly sealed, the return address looks right, and the handwriting matches. Do you open it? In most threat models, yes. Authentication passed. But what if the letter asks you to wire $400,000 to an offshore account? The identity check told you <em>who sent it.</em> It said nothing about whether the request made sense.</p>

  <p>This is, roughly, the situation we're in with AI agents.</p>

  <p>Autonomous agents — coding agents, research crawlers, RPA bots, orchestration runtimes, every variety of "agentic AI" that is proliferating across enterprise infrastructure right now — are increasingly capable of taking consequential action. They write code and commit it. They query databases. They call APIs, move files, send emails, provision cloud resources, and sometimes authorize financial transactions. And they do this with credentials. Real credentials. Often the same credentials a human engineer would use, granted with the same (or more) permissions, and audited at exactly the same level: a log entry that says <em>the token was valid</em>.</p>

  <p>The identity industry has spent thirty years building sophisticated authentication infrastructure. SAML, OAuth 2.0, OIDC, mTLS, FIDO2, SPIFFE/SPIRE — the list of protocols for establishing <em>who</em> something is has grown impressively long. What we don't have — what we never really needed until now — is a framework for establishing <em>why.</em></p>

  <h2>Non-Human Identity, But Worse</h2>

  <p>The term NHI — non-human identity — has been circulating in IAM circles for a few years, usually applied to service accounts, CI/CD pipeline tokens, and API keys. Security teams treat NHIs as a management problem: they proliferate, they rarely rotate, they accumulate access, and when they're compromised, the blast radius is hard to contain. All of this is true. The Midnight Blizzard breach of Microsoft's corporate email in 2023 pivoted through an OAuth application that had excessive privileges. The CircleCI breach in 2022 originated with a stolen session token. The pattern is consistent and familiar.</p>

  <p>But agentic AI is a different class of NHI, and the difference matters. A service account makes a single API call: <code>GET /user/{id}</code>, or <code>POST /deploy</code>. The action is atomic, discrete, and — in a well-designed system — auditable as a unit. A coding agent, by contrast, runs a <em>sequence</em> of operations that only makes sense as a narrative. It reads a file, then searches for related files, then modifies several of them, then commits the result, then — because it found something suspicious — opens a pull request and pings a human reviewer. The actions are individually unremarkable. The intent behind them is what matters. And intent is invisible to every authentication and authorization primitive we currently have.</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>We know how to ask: <em>Is this principal allowed to call this endpoint?</em> We do not know how to ask: <em>Does this sequence of calls make sense given why this agent was invoked?</em></p>
  </blockquote>

  <p>This is the agent identity gap. It's not a gap in authentication — OAuth and JWT handle that adequately. It's a gap in the semantic layer between authentication and authorization. Between proving identity and proving purpose.</p>

  <h2>The Overprivilege Default</h2>

  <p>In practice, most organizations address this gap with a familiar workaround: they don't. Agents run with whatever credentials the deploying engineer had available — typically overprivileged service accounts or developer tokens provisioned under time pressure, with no scope narrowing, no session context, and no mechanism for revoking access mid-task. The agent gets a key to the building and the instructions "do something useful." This is not negligence; it's the only option available given current tooling.</p>

  <p>The consequences are already showing up. GitHub Copilot agents and similar tools regularly receive repository-wide access when file-specific access would be sufficient. Autonomous research agents scrape internal document stores with the permissions of the person who configured them — which is often an IT administrator. When something goes wrong, the audit log shows a valid credential performing valid operations. The word "unauthorized" never appears, because technically nothing was unauthorized. The authorization model simply had no way to express "this agent should not have been doing that."</p>

  <p>Least-privilege is one response, and it's necessary but not sufficient. Limiting an agent to read-only access on a specific repository prevents some failure modes. It doesn't address the case where a compromised or misbehaving agent does something semantically wrong using its legitimately scoped access. An agent with read-only access to your customer database can still exfiltrate all of it. The authorization primitive — <em>read is allowed</em> — can't distinguish between "read one record to answer a support query" and "read all records to build a training dataset."</p>

  <h2>What Intent-Scoped Tokens Look Like</h2>

  <p>The idea of scoping credentials to a declared intent is not new in theory. Capabilities-based security, OAuth's scope parameter, ABAC policies — these all gesture toward it. But they operate at the resource level, not the purpose level. A token scoped to <code>repo:read</code> expresses nothing about what the read is for.</p>

  <p>What we actually need is a way to encode a task context into the credential itself — or alongside it — such that downstream authorization decisions can interrogate not just "who is asking" but "what is this agent trying to accomplish, and does this action make sense in that context?"</p>

  <p>In the matterunknown council architecture, we've been working on exactly this problem in a small way. The Guardian system — our authorization layer for a small network of autonomous agents — issues what we call intent-scoped tokens. When an agent like Reid (a research agent) is invoked to answer a question, it receives a short-lived token that carries a declared task context: the nature of the query, the data categories it's expected to touch, and a hard boundary on what actions fall outside that scope. Guardian evaluates every action against the declared intent, not just against a permission list. If Reid, mid-task, attempts to access a credentials store it has no reason to touch given the declared query, that action fails — not because the permission list excludes it, but because Guardian's policy layer recognizes it as semantically anomalous.</p>

  <p>We're not presenting this as a general solution — the system is bespoke, runs at small scale, and has significant rough edges. We mention it because it demonstrates the problem is architecturally tractable. Intent-scoped authorization isn't a moonshot. It's an engineering problem that existing primitives (JWT claims, SPIFFE SVIDs, OPA policies) can be extended to support. What's missing is the industry-level standardization to make it composable.</p>

  <h2>The Audit Trail Problem</h2>

  <p>Authorization is only half the gap. The other half is observability. Even if we solved intent-scoped tokens tomorrow, we'd still face the challenge of building audit trails that capture <em>action sequences</em> rather than individual operations. Current SIEM infrastructure was designed for atomic events: <code>login attempt from IP x</code>, <code>file accessed by user y</code>. Stringing those events into a coherent narrative of "what was the agent trying to accomplish, and did it succeed?" requires tooling that doesn't exist in any mature, standardized form.</p>

  <p>What we need is something closer to a flight recorder than a syslog: a structured trace of the agent's task, its sub-goals, the actions it took in pursuit of each, and the points at which it deviated from expected behavior. This is sometimes called "agent observability" in the emerging MLOps literature, but it's more than performance monitoring. It's forensic infrastructure. When an agent causes harm — whether through compromise, misconfiguration, or simply being wrong in a consequential way — you need to be able to reconstruct <em>what the agent thought it was doing</em> alongside what it actually did.</p>

  <p>Without this, incident response for agentic systems looks like trying to reconstruct a crime from a pile of individual video frames, sorted randomly, with no timestamps.</p>

  <h2>The Question We Keep Not Asking</h2>

  <p>There's a design sensibility baked deep into identity infrastructure that has served us well for decades: identity is about entities, and authorization is about what those entities can do. The subject-predicate-object model — <em>Alice can read the file</em> — is clean, auditable, and maps naturally to access control lists. It also completely fails to capture the semantics of an autonomous agent operating over time toward a goal.</p>

  <p>The question we keep not asking is: what is this agent <em>for?</em> Not in a philosophical sense — in a technical, policy-enforceable sense. What task was it invoked to perform? What information does it legitimately need to perform that task? What actions are consistent with that task, and which are anomalous? These are hard questions to operationalize, but they're the right questions. And we will not build trustworthy agentic infrastructure until the identity and authorization stack is capable of asking them.</p>

  <p>The agent identity gap isn't a bug waiting to be patched. It's a conceptual hole in the foundation. Authentication proves who. Authorization constrains what. We have no primitive, today, that expresses <em>why</em> — and until we do, every AI agent we deploy is operating in a trust vacuum, credentialed and largely unaccountable.</p>

  <p>That's a fine way to build a demo. It is not a fine way to build infrastructure.</p>

